<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-148-321 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 798 661</DOCID><JOURNAL>PC Week  May 27 1991 v8 n21 p40(1)* Full Text COPYRIGHT Ziff-Davis Publishing Co. 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Graphics program lets users work in 4 presentations. (ChartersoftCorp.'s GraphShow) (product announcement)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Company:   Chartersoft Corp. (Product introduction).andO;Product:   GraphShow (Presentation software) (Product introduction).andO;Topic:     Product IntroductionPresentation Software.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>Chartersoft Corp. last week introduced a new presentation-graphics packagethat allows users to work with as many as four presentations at one time.andM;In addition, GraphShow lets users create master pages, to make the appearanceof presentations more consistent, and produce 3-D charts, according toChartersoft officials.andM;Users also can link spreadsheet data to allow other users to update data incharts using links to files in Lotus Development Corp.'s 1-2-3 spreadsheetand ASCII files.andM;The program also supports graphics files produced by WordPerfect Corp.'sWordPerfect, Microsoft Corp.'s Word, Aldus Corp.'s PageMaker and VenturaSoftware Inc.'s Ventura Publisher.andM;The $495 graphics program comes with 80 predefined graph types and 500clip-art files.andP;  Slated to be shipped this week, GraphShow will come with 13Adobe typefaces.andM;The Winnipeg, Manitoba, startup is one of a growing list of vendors jumpinginto the Windows presentation-graphics market, including Lotus, IBM and AldusDevelopment Corp.andM;Chartersoft can be contacted at (204) 453-4444.andO;</TEXT></DOC>